1
00:00:00,099 --> 00:00:04,870
Where's my jumper from? Er, it's Gucc— No, it's my grandma's. I think she knitted it.

2
00:00:04,870 --> 00:00:05,908
I look really wholesome.

3
00:00:05,908 --> 00:00:14,886
And the fact it was from my grandma, it's like a hug, innit.

4
00:00:14,886 --> 00:00:18,486
My name is Will Gao. I'm an actor and a musician.

5
00:00:18,486 --> 00:00:19,704
This chair's wonky.

6
00:00:19,704 --> 00:00:21,874
As you can see, we're in a forest.

7
00:00:21,874 --> 00:00:24,999
Jessie is, like, three years old. Jessie

8
00:00:24,999 --> 00:00:27,500
I give her, like, cheeky bits of cheese.

9
00:00:27,500 --> 00:00:28,687
I want to be her favorite.

10
00:00:28,687 --> 00:00:31,537
I don't know many different types of cheeses, but Cheddar, yeah?

11
00:00:31,537 --> 00:00:33,654
Maybe if she's lucky, Camembert.

12
00:00:33,654 --> 00:00:35,500
What's the squi— That's the squidgy one, isn't it?

13
00:00:35,500 --> 00:00:37,651
Yeah. This is her main stomping ground.

14
00:00:37,651 --> 00:00:41,720
We're in Croydon right now. My stomping ground as well.

15
00:00:41,720 --> 00:00:48,366
My mum's Chinese, and my dad's English, and we grew up kind of in both cultures, in Chinese culture and also English culture.

16
00:00:48,366 --> 00:00:55,962
I was the oldest child with my little sister, who I'm also in a band with and I work with very closely, and then my little brother as well.

17
00:00:55,962 --> 00:01:00,278
So, my dad's English, and he doesn't speak any Chinese.

18
00:01:00,278 --> 00:01:03,661
He doesn't really speak— Yeah, he tried, but it didn't work out.

19
00:01:03,661 --> 00:01:08,961
But my mum's Chinese, and she kind of grew up speaking to me in Chinese, so I kind of have a vocabulary.

20
00:01:08,961 --> 00:01:10,921
Mostly when she was angry at me.

21
00:01:10,921 --> 00:01:16,764
Like, when she's getting annoyed, it'll be in Chinese, so I know a lot of, like, rude and naughty words in Chinese.

22
00:01:16,764 --> 00:01:18,388
Bèn dàn. It means "silly egg." "

23
00:01:18,388 --> 00:01:20,173
My mum used to call me a bèn dàn a lot at the time.

24
00:01:20,173 --> 00:01:27,116
I went to an all-boys school throughout my whole education, and I just didn't feel, like, this sense of belonging that a lot of my friends felt.

25
00:01:27,116 --> 00:01:30,160
And I think that was, like, a really big part of my childhood.

26
00:01:30,160 --> 00:01:39,474
But now it's great because I'm in a place where I get to explore that a lot, and I really get to, like, dissect why that is and why I was feeling like that.

27
00:01:39,474 --> 00:01:44,621
It actually clicked when I saw a play in London called The Great Wave.

28
00:01:44,621 --> 00:01:47,503
It was at the National Theatre, and it was an all East Asian cast.

29
00:01:47,503 --> 00:01:52,453
And I had this overwhelming sense of inclusivity, and I got to meet a couple of the actors afterwards.

30
00:01:52,453 --> 00:01:53,836
It was pretty cool.

31
00:01:53,836 --> 00:02:09,743
I feel the pressure of being one of few British East Asian actors who are leading the industry, I guess, or being the most visible, so I feel that need to be able to speak about this issue and to be really honest about it.

32
00:02:09,743 --> 00:02:11,773
I didn't feel represented on screen.

33
00:02:11,773 --> 00:02:15,273
On television, especially in the UK, we have such an issue with representation.

34
00:02:15,273 --> 00:02:24,583
Only now I'm starting to see East Asian … British East Asian actors being represented in acting and in our industry in general.

35
00:02:24,583 --> 00:02:32,647
I think it's been really recent, and we've got a long way to go, but we're nowhere near where we need to get … so yeah.

36
00:02:32,647 --> 00:02:41,216
My dad was an actor, a true theater actor, and a lot of his friends are in that kind of creative world and space.

37
00:02:41,216 --> 00:02:52,284
And I think I looked up to my mum and dad's love of culture and art, and I think that really influenced me growing up, and I think a couple of teachers at school as well.

38
00:02:52,284 --> 00:02:57,612
I think music and the world of theater and performance are very linked together.

39
00:02:57,612 --> 00:03:05,238
My school was connected with a commercial boys choir, and so I spent four years doing a lot of opera, which is a really niche thing.

40
00:03:05,238 --> 00:03:13,336
But I learned a lot more about music, and also it gave me a great opportunity to practice acting because opera's very … very dramatic and intense.

41
00:03:13,336 --> 00:03:18,800
Beijing opera, like, the "Ba!", like, that stuff, yeah, that's … that's really intense.

42
00:03:18,800 --> 00:03:24,157
I went to one in Beijing. It's, like, one hour of organized carnage.

43
00:03:24,157 --> 00:03:34,388
I remember performing in a Shakespeare opera, A Midsummer Night's Dream by Benjamin Britten, and I was playing one of the fairies.

44
00:03:34,388 --> 00:03:36,756
So I spent a few years doing that, and then my voice broke.

45
00:03:36,756 --> 00:03:38,367
I got fired.

46
00:03:38,367 --> 00:03:52,874
But I still enjoy music, and I still enjoyed acting, but I was forced to go back to school, which was shit.

47
00:03:52,874 --> 00:03:58,111
My mum always said, like, "Just keep at it."

48
00:03:58,111 --> 00:04:05,794
My mum was like, "Just keep going because at some point you'll be able to … come back."

49
00:04:05,794 --> 00:04:09,051
"And realize that the hard work paid off," you know. "

50
00:04:09,051 --> 00:04:15,069
Yeah. My mum and my dad, they cared a lot about my education and, like, what I was up to.

51
00:04:15,069 --> 00:04:21,099
But then when I was like, "You know what?" "Actually, I want to be an actor. I want to be a musician." "I want to be creative," they were pretty supportive of it, actually.

52
00:04:21,099 --> 00:04:27,966
I was blessed in that respect.

53
00:04:27,966 --> 00:04:33,444
The scariest moment of my life? You're just rushed out, and suddenly there's a camera, like, "boomph," and I forgot my line completely.

54
00:04:33,444 --> 00:04:36,735
You've got a lot of people around. Got used to it, though.

55
00:04:36,735 --> 00:04:50,099
Two months after Heartstopper came out, I was walking down the street, and there's a group of young girls, and one of them, like, broke down crying, like, kind of seeing me, and then—I think they'd just seen the show.&nbsp;

56
00:04:50,099 --> 00:04:59,524
It had such a profound impact on so many people, and it really helped people discover themselves and realize that they had a place and a group that they were accepted into.

57
00:04:59,524 --> 00:05:04,875
I think the great thing about having an ensemble cast and a cast of, I mean, we're all the same age, right?

58
00:05:04,875 --> 00:05:11,231
We're all between the ages of, like, 17 and 22, 23, so we're all there to support each other, and I think it was such a huge moment for all of us.

59
00:05:11,231 --> 00:05:16,683
I remember giving many a call to some of my castmates to check in with them, see if they were OK.

60
00:05:16,683 --> 00:05:33,060
Life just turned up a notch, like, the noise of life, and also the accelerator pedal was like "vrooooph."

61
00:05:33,060 --> 00:05:38,343
Sebastian Croft, I had a long-ass streak with him that ended when I deleted Snapchat.

62
00:05:38,343 --> 00:05:41,732
I learned a lot about the history of the LGBT community.

63
00:05:41,732 --> 00:05:46,393
I explored Stonewall and gay rights movement and how little there actually has been.

64
00:05:46,393 --> 00:05:57,881
And it was really empowering to be part of that show because, like, this show is, like, the first show that's really celebrating it and not just using it as some, like, negative spin-off.

65
00:05:57,881 --> 00:05:59,588
I did a bit of modeling for a bit.

66
00:05:59,588 --> 00:06:03,035
I was, like, in East Croydon Station, as you do.

67
00:06:03,035 --> 00:06:08,376
And this lady came up to me, and she was like … "Well, what's your name?"

68
00:06:08,376 --> 00:06:10,196
I was like, "Will," and she kind of scouted me.

69
00:06:10,196 --> 00:06:12,417
I thought it was, like, a scam, but it turned out it was legit.

70
00:06:12,417 --> 00:06:17,999
I had some crazy stories from it, like fashion show afterparties are … they're nuts.

71
00:06:17,999 --> 00:06:19,360
Underage. Shh.

72
00:06:19,360 --> 00:06:25,170
I've gone to Beijing quite a few times in my life because my grandparents are there, and a lot of my family are there.

73
00:06:25,170 --> 00:06:29,278
Seeing my grandma LaoLao in the outskirts of Beijing and just stay there with her.

74
00:06:29,278 --> 00:06:33,589
She cooked many a meal.

75
00:06:33,589 --> 00:06:40,507
Beijing to London, I'd love to bring those stalls with, like, hot peanuts and, like, snacks and traditional Chinese pancakes.

76
00:06:40,507 --> 00:06:44,991
I think it's the breakfast food there, like bao buns and, like, baozi.

77
00:06:44,991 --> 00:06:51,347
I remember every time we'd get there, like, in the morning, my grandmother would prepare them, like, fresh from the market.

78
00:06:51,347 --> 00:06:53,446
I think Croydon could do with some of those.

79
00:06:53,446 --> 00:06:58,716
Chinese food is just the vibe.

80
00:06:58,716 --> 00:07:02,283
My dad's knowledge of cooking, like, he had, like, one recipe book.

81
00:07:02,283 --> 00:07:06,006
He had a Delia Smith cookbook, and he followed that like religion.

82
00:07:06,006 --> 00:07:13,891
Whereas my mum kind of improvised, and she had that training from … passed down from, like, grandparents, great-grandparents.

83
00:07:13,891 --> 00:07:17,783
I can't handle spicy food. I literally can't handle it.

84
00:07:17,783 --> 00:07:24,691
I'm a … I'm a shame to my mum.

85
00:07:24,691 --> 00:07:33,997
Introducing— Oh, my sister's not here.&nbsp; Me and Olivia, who's my wonderful and very talented sister, started a band called Wasia Project in 2018.

86
00:07:33,997 --> 00:07:38,765
But then it kind of started to build, and we started doing shows, and we released an EP that did really well.

87
00:07:38,765 --> 00:07:48,508
And then we've kind of been thrown into this kind of chaos of releasing music and being in the studio and going to gigs, and it's been really, really fun.

88
00:07:48,508 --> 00:07:51,391
Most songs now, we both do together.

89
00:07:51,391 --> 00:08:02,747
Like, I'll bring an idea, she'll develop it, we'll sit in a room, talk about it, and then when we produce it, obviously, we're there together … arguing, but healthy, healthy arguing.

90
00:08:02,747 --> 00:08:05,013
Also, songwriting's such a vulnerable thing.

91
00:08:05,013 --> 00:08:15,277
I think, especially at times where I've been quite low or written songs that are quite sad, and vice versa for her, we've been uncomfortable to share it, but we know exactly what the vibe is.

92
00:08:15,277 --> 00:08:20,977
Like, we'll turn, face away from each other, and, like, it's really sweet.

93
00:08:20,977 --> 00:08:26,406
ABBA and Queen and, like, The Beatles were, like, an underscore for my whole childhood. ABBA、Queen

94
00:08:26,406 --> 00:08:35,226
And me and my sister, there's so many home movies of just us, like, dancing to, like, ABBA and just hearing these sounds that made me want to move and perform.

95
00:08:35,226 --> 00:08:39,717
I think my dad played more ABBA, and he played The Beatles, a lot of The Beatles, and Frank Sinatra.

96
00:08:39,717 --> 00:08:48,514
And then my mum played, like, a lot of Bee Gees, a lot of Carpenters, and they're a big influence now for me and my sister because, obviously, the Carpenters were siblings as well.

97
00:08:48,514 --> 00:08:54,709
It's such a privilege to say that I literally get to make music with my sister for a living.

98
00:08:54,709 --> 00:08:56,726
It's just mad.

99
00:08:56,726 --> 00:08:59,819
I think I'm quite a frantic person, especially before gigs.

100
00:08:59,819 --> 00:09:03,812
I'm quite nervous, and I'm high energy and frantic, and she's really chilled.

101
00:09:03,812 --> 00:09:12,747
She's collected, and she's calm, and it's like yin and yang.

102
00:09:12,747 --> 00:09:15,632
The idea comes from scratch when you're writing a song.

103
00:09:15,632 --> 00:09:22,995
It comes from nothing, or it comes from an emotion, feeling, like sadness or happiness or love or friendship, and you attach them.

104
00:09:22,995 --> 00:09:24,610
It's such a raw kind of craft.

105
00:09:24,610 --> 00:09:29,450
Whereas with acting, I think you're bringing … you're finding the emotion within a piece of writing.

106
00:09:29,450 --> 00:09:33,769
That's the biggest difference.

107
00:09:33,769 --> 00:09:35,657
There are challenges, like, everywhere you go.

108
00:09:35,657 --> 00:09:49,871
But for me, with acting and music, believing in myself was a big thing.

109
00:09:49,871 --> 00:09:57,163
Yeah. Mitski is an artist that is just …so interesting in just everything she's been doing.

110
00:09:57,163 --> 00:10:00,287
Dream collab would be with Mitski.

111
00:10:00,287 --> 00:10:03,139
So if Mitski's seeing this, please.

112
00:10:03,139 --> 00:10:07,005
I saw her live at the Roundhouse, and she is just insane.

113
00:10:07,005 --> 00:10:11,477
Just the whole soundworld she's created is like … just such a fusion.

114
00:10:11,477 --> 00:10:24,638
It's like … it's a love letter to, like, 1980s Japan, but it's also just through, like, the lens of modern-day pop, which is just so inspiring for me and Olivia.

115
00:10:24,638 --> 00:10:27,688
I just kind of try and stay disconnected from social media.

116
00:10:27,688 --> 00:10:31,299
I try and stay in real life as I possibly can.

117
00:10:31,299 --> 00:10:36,552
But TikTok is becoming a very broad platform now, and I think it's not just TikTok dances.

118
00:10:36,552 --> 00:10:38,625
There's so many people doing so many different things.

119
00:10:38,625 --> 00:10:43,424
So I actually think I need to embrace TikTok more than I have been.

120
00:10:43,424 --> 00:10:47,562
Not doing TikTok dances because that would be very embarrassing, and I wouldn't want to do that.

121
00:10:47,562 --> 00:10:50,432
My dancing will never be seen.

122
00:10:50,432 --> 00:10:52,829
Like, yeah, that's not— That … that can't happen.

123
00:10:52,829 --> 00:10:54,642
No one can see my— Yeah, no.

124
00:10:54,642 --> 00:10:58,959
I think I'm going to stick with the music and the acting as the main … as the main thing.

125
00:10:58,959 --> 00:11:08,686
I want to, like, fuse my two kind of worlds into one and explore, like, projects that incorporate both.

126
00:11:08,686 --> 00:11:13,884
Jessie was born … three years ago. She was a tiny puppy.

127
00:11:13,884 --> 00:11:22,027
And we called her Jessie because I think … I can't remember.

128
00:11:22,027 --> 00:11:26,045
And then I just remember walking her lots and caring for her.

129
00:11:26,045 --> 00:11:33,769
Yeah, I really like Jessie, but she does literally the stinkiest poos, like, it's actually—

130
00:11:33,769 --> 00:11:37,283
You saw today, the poos, like, it was literally abysmal.

131
00:11:37,283 --> 00:11:39,783
I hope this doesn't make the final cut.

